rt among both academic experts and policymakers, and while the countries that have followed this model have generally experienced good macroeconomic outcomes, many important questions about inflation targeting remain. In Inflation Targeting, a distinguished group of contributors explores the many underexamined dimensions of inflation targeting—its potential, its successes, and its limitations—from both a theoretical and an empirical standpoint, and for both developed and emerging economies. The volume opens with a discussion of the optimal formulation of inflation-targeting policy and continues with a debate about the desirability of such a model for the United States. The concluding chapters discuss the special problems of inflation targeting in emerging markets, including the Czech Republic, Poland, and Hungary.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBusiness. 0aInflation (Finance). 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  ainflation, economics, monetary policy, macroeconomics, emerging markets, hungary, poland, czech republic, central banks, chile, constraint, equilibrium, emu, exchange rates, federal reserve, greenspan, growth, output, fiscal policies, nonfiction, imperfect knowledge, israel, japan, price, stability, sweden, switzerland, targeting, transparency, variables, wages.1 aBall, Laurence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernanke, Ben S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernanke, Ben S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCaballero, Ricardo J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecchetti, Stephen G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiannoni, Marc P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodfriend, Marvin, 